s, and Montaigne’s Essays. Eden concludes by showing how these rhetorical practices were understood to work together to form a literary masterwork, with important implications for how we read these texts today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aEuropean literatureyRenaissance, 1450-1600xClassical influences. 0aRhetoric, AncientxInfluence. 0aRhetoric, Renaissance. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  atacitus, quintilian, cicero, aristotle, plato, rhetoric, style, similitude, refutation, status, essays, montaigne, ciceronianus, antibarbarians, erasmus, book of the courtier, castiglione, secret, petrarch, literature, structure, narrative theory, linguistics, nonfiction, renaissance, classicism, manuscripts, argument, reception, influence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226821276423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226821276/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles